<!-- 01 INTRO / WHY FREEZERS DIFFER -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · Reach-in freezer service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">A reach-in freezer is not just a colder cooler. The defrost architecture is fundamentally different.</h2>

    <p>Coolers run off-cycle defrost: the refrigerant cycles off, ambient cabinet air melts the frost on the evaporator. Freezers cannot do this. At a -5°F target, the cabinet air is too cold to melt evaporator frost. So freezers use <strong>electric defrost</strong>: a heating element wraps the evaporator coil and runs on a timer, typically 4 to 6 cycles per 24 hours, 15 to 30 minutes each. When the defrost system fails, the freezer becomes a frozen brick or warms above safe temp. Both are emergencies.</p>

    <p>We service commercial reach-in freezers across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside counties. Single-door, double-door, triple-door. All major brands. The most common units we see: True T-23F (single-door freezer), True T-49F (the freezer twin of the T-49 cooler, two-door), Turbo Air M3F line, Traulsen G/R Series freezers, Beverage-Air HF1 and HF2 freezers, Continental, Hoshizaki commercial, Victory.</p>

    <p>EPA 608 Universal, required for any sealed system work. CSLB #1138898. BHGS Licensed #A49573. BBB A+. 24/7 phones answered, no after-hours surcharge.</p>

    <p>For walk-in cold storage, see <a href="/commercial/refrigeration/walk-in-freezer-repair/">walk-in freezer repair</a>. For cooler reach-ins (above-freezing units, off-cycle defrost), see <a href="/commercial/refrigeration/reach-in-cooler-repair/">reach-in cooler repair</a>. Both are different repair scopes than this page.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 TYPICAL FREEZER FAILURES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Typical freezer failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What fails on commercial reach-in freezers, in rough order of frequency.</h2>

    <ol class="failure-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Electric defrost heater element burnout (year 5 to 8), most common freezer-specific failure.</strong>
        Defrost heater wraps the evaporator coil. When the heater opens (electrical open circuit), defrost cycles still run on the timer but no heat is applied. Frost builds, builds, builds. Eventually the evaporator becomes a solid ice block, airflow stops, freezer warms to 25 to 30°F. Replacement requires accessing the evaporator: 2 to 3 hour repair. $380 to $680 part plus labor.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Defrost timer / defrost termination thermostat.</strong>
        Two failure modes: stuck-in-defrost (heater runs continuously, freezer warms) or never-defrost (frost builds permanently). The termination thermostat tells the defrost cycle when to stop. When it fails, the cycle either runs too long or doesn't run at all.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Drain heater (drain pan or drain line heater).</strong>
        Freezer drain water from the defrost cycle freezes if the drain heater fails. Water back-floods, refreezes, blocks the defrost drain, freezer floods, or develops ice on the cabinet floor. $200 to $340.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Condenser fan motor.</strong>
        Same wear pattern as a cooler: 4 to 6 year coastal life. Drives condensing-unit cooling. Replacement $280 to $500.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Evaporator fan motor.</strong>
        Same as cooler: circulates cold air over food product. $260 to $450.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Door gasket failure.</strong>
        Heavy-duty freezer gaskets compress more slowly than cooler gaskets but still 4 to 6 years on heavy-use. Compressed gasket on a freezer means warm-air infiltration, which means continuous frost build, which means defrost cycles can't keep up, which means the system runs constantly. $200 to $380 per door.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Refrigerant slow leak.</strong>
        EPA 608 leak repair before recharge. Reach-in freezers typically use R-404A or R-448A.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Compressor failure (year 8 to 15).</strong>
        Mechanical wear. This is the replace-vs-repair decision threshold on most reach-in freezers.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Door anti-condensation heaters (around door frame).</strong>
        Prevent ice buildup at the door frame seal. When they fail, ice forms at the door, the door doesn't close cleanly, warm air infiltrates. Common at year 6 to 9.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 WHY FREEZERS BREAK DIFFERENTLY -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Diagnostic distinction</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Why freezers break differently than coolers.</h2>

    <p>Coolers run off-cycle defrost: no defrost components, just the refrigerant cycle. Freezers run electric defrost, which adds 4 components that don't exist on a cooler: defrost heater, defrost timer, defrost termination thermostat, and drain heater. These 4 components are why <strong>roughly 70% of freezer-specific failures aren't possible on a cooler.</strong></p>

    <p>If you've had a tech work on your freezer who diagnosed it like a cooler, wrong tools, wrong tests, wrong parts, that's the issue. Reach-in freezer service requires understanding the electric defrost cycle architecture, the timer-thermostat-heater interaction, and the freezer-specific drain and door-frame heaters. We do.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL REPAIR STORIES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Recent freezer repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Composite stories from the route.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Five reach-in freezer jobs from the past 90 days. Models, symptoms, diagnosis, parts, time, total. Names omitted; the technical scenarios are typical of what we see weekly.</p>

    <div class="story-grid">
      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Restaurant in Beverly Hills · True T-49F two-door, 8 years old</h3>
        <p>Saturday morning, freezer at 25°F (target -5°F). Diagnosed: defrost heater element open-circuited. Replaced element with True OEM, accessed via evaporator panel. Tested 2 defrost cycles, monitored pulldown to -5°F over 5 hours. Total: $120 + $485 part + 2.5 hours = $810. Common 8-year failure pattern.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Bakery in Pasadena · Turbo Air M3F47 single-door, 6 years old</h3>
        <p>Frost building on evaporator visibly through cabinet vents, freezer warming. Diagnosed: defrost termination thermostat failed (defrost cycles starting but not stopping properly, ice melting then refreezing thicker). Replaced thermostat. Total: $120 + $185 part + 1.5 hours = $385.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Hotel in Santa Monica · Traulsen G22010 single-door, 11 years old</h3>
        <p>Water on cabinet floor plus ice forming around door. Diagnosed: drain heater failed (water freezing in drain line, back-flooding) AND door anti-condensation heater failed (creating door frame ice). Replaced both. Total: $120 + $420 parts + 2 hours = $720. Multi-component coastal failure pattern.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Restaurant on Sunset, West Hollywood · Beverage-Air HF2-1S two-door, 9 years old</h3>
        <p>Temp climbing to 12°F. Diagnosed: refrigerant leak at evaporator coil (R-404A). EPA 608 leak repair: pumped down, brazed coil joint, vacuum to 500 microns, recharged R-404A. Pulldown to -3°F in 4 hours. Total: $120 + $580 refrigerant + $720 labor + leak detection = $1,540.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Pizza shop in Marina del Rey · True T-23F single-door, 13 years old</h3>
        <p>Multiple cascading failures: defrost heater open + condenser fan motor seized + door gasket compressed flat. Owner asked replace-vs-repair. Quoted $1,800 for full repair. Replacement equivalent T-23F installed runs $4,500+. Approved repair, all three components done in single visit (4 hours). Total: $120 + $980 parts + 4 hours = $1,820. 5+ years more service life expected.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 HONEST SCOPE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Honest scope</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we service, what we don't.</h2>

    <p><strong>We service:</strong> all commercial reach-in freezer brands and configurations, single, double, and triple door. Pass-through models. Glass-door freezer merchandisers. All EPA-permitted refrigerants (R-404A, R-448A, and current low-GWP transitions).</p>

    <p><strong>We don't do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="scope-list">
      <li><strong>New reach-in freezer installation.</strong> Specialty installer trade. We coordinate with installers when replacement is the right call.</li>
      <li><strong>Blast freezer or shock freezer repair.</strong> Different technology, different trade. We refer.</li>
      <li><strong>Ice cream display freezer specialty work outside the reach-in scope.</strong> The merchandiser-style display freezers we service; the rapid-pull display systems used by some ice cream operations are a separate specialty.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

